colNames = list(file1.columns)[0:-1]    # taking only non-classifier columns
train_set, valid_set, t_y, v_y = train_test_split(file1[colNames], file1['isFraud'], test_size=0.3)   # splitting the data into training and validation sets from dataset

train_stand = scale.fit_transform(train_set)    # scaled data
valid_stand = scale.fit_transform(valid_set)

Conclusion:¶

From the dataset Fradulant data acquired from Kaggle website, I created a machine learning model that predict whether it is Fraud or Not-Fraud based on certain criteria. I used twe pre-defined models such as Logistic Regression model and KNeigbour model to train the data set. On my research, I able produce the following result on both model,
Model 1: Logistic Regression

  • Model Accuracy: 0.9991947761561537
  • Precision Score: 0.8933884297520661
  • Recall Score: 0.43431096826034554
Model 2: KNeigbour Classifier Model
  • Model Accuracy: 0.9994855368805093
  • Precision Score: 0.95364238410596031
  • Recall Score: 0.6364001607071113

The KNeigbour Classifier perform well compared to Logistic Regression due to the algorithm chose by KNeighbour model.

Data set source: kaggle
